oys\\n- Post-Tang decline and Ming rebuild (city walls ~1370)\\n- Muslim quarter + Great Mosque of Xi\'an (founded 742 CE)\\n- Xi\'an Incident (December 1936) — Chiang Kai-shek kidnapped, forced anti-Japanese united front\\n- Modern Xi\'an: industrial + tourism + UNESCO sites\\n\\nFor each era: 1-2 paragraphs + 3-5 bullet facts. Cite sources inline (URL or book + page where possible). Prioritise primary/academic sources over blog aggregators.\\n\\n### 2. Terracotta Army deep dive\\n\\nCold-open anchor. Cover:\\n- Discovery: 1974, farmers Yang Zhifa + family, digging a well in Lintong district\\n- Construction scale: 700,000+ workers (per Sima Qian\'s Shiji), 38+ years of building\\n- Army: ~8,000 figures, individualised faces (theories: 10 base molds + modifications), originally painted, horses + chariots\\n- Weapons: bronze + iron, survived 2200 years due to chrome-plating (technology \\"rediscovered\\" 20th century)\\n- Central tomb: Qin Shi Huang mausoleum still UNEXCAVATED due to mercury contamination (Shiji claims \\"rivers of mercury\\") and preservation fears\\n- UNESCO WH 1987\\n- Current SEO keywords associated (what EN-speaking viewers search)\\n\\n### 3. Silk Road role (Han + Tang)\\n\\nWhy Xi\'an matters globally. Volume of trade, routes, commodities, cross-cultural exchanges (Buddhism arrival, Nestorian stele 781 CE, Arab/Persian merchants in Tang).\\n\\n### 4. Anecdotes & narrative beats\\n\\nList 10-15 specific incidents, people, or material objects that would make compelling visual/narrative beats in a 7-10min documentary. Examples:\\n- Yang Zhifa digging the well\\n- Sima Qian writing the first account of the mausoleum\\n- Empress Wu Zetian (only female emperor in Chinese history, ruled from Xi\'an)\\n- Nestorian stele\'s Syriac inscription\\n- 1936 kidnapping in the Huaqing Pool hot spring resort\\n- Poet Li Bai\'s Tang-era Chang\'an nightlife\\n\\nFor each: date, 1-sentence visual summary, why it resonates for non-Chinese audience.\\n\\n### 5. Audience expectations & anti-clickbait framing\\n\\nWhat does the target viewer (Anglo Anglo-sphere Lay Historian persona + Japan/China curious secondary) already know about Xi\'an? Common pop-culture hooks (Tomb Raider 2, Disney\'s Mulan references, etc.) — list them so script can AVOID low-quality re-treads. What DO they NOT know that would be genuinely surprising?\\n\\n### 6. SEO keyword landscape (2026)\\n\\nCurrent top-searched Xi\'an terms on YouTube. Rising keywords (Google Trends 7-day, 30-day). Competitor analysis: 5-8 existing YouTube videos on Xi\'an that perform well, their hook strategies, title + thumbnail patterns, average retention. What gaps exist?\\n\\n### 7. Sources cited\\n\\nBibliography. Prioritise: academic (JSTOR, university press), museum/UNESCO primary, Sima Qian\'s Records of the Grand Historian (Shiji) as primary Qin-era source, verified history documentaries. Avoid Wikipedia as sole citation — use it only to find primary refs.\\n\\n### 8. Open questions for Phase 1\\n\\nList 5-10 ambiguities that Phase 1 (audience persona + retention arch) must resolve before SCRIPT.md can be written. Examples: \\"3 eras or 4?\\", \\"Terracotta Army cold-open at 0-15s or 0-30s?\\", \\"include Xi\'an Incident 1936 or stop at Tang?\\", \\"Russian translation track?\\", etc.\\n\\n## Style requirements\\n\\n- Factual, analytical, non-marketing tone.\\n- Name specific sources inline — e.g. \\"Portal, *The Terracotta Warriors of Qin Shihuang*, Cambridge UP 2007 p.42\\" or \\"UNESCO WH inscription 441, 1987\\".\\n- No slop phrases (breathtaking, captivating, mesmerizing, etc.).\\n- Tables for chronology and SEO keyword inventory.\\n- Russian + English place names where useful (西安 / Сиань / Xi\'an).\\n\\n## Priority\\n\\nPhase 0 must be RIGOROUS — the rest of the pipeline depends on its factual backbone. If a fact is uncertain, mark it `[VERIFY]` and note what source would confirm.\\n\\nUse WebSearch / hf_doc_search / arxiv_search as needed. Cite actively.\\n\\nSub